<body>
<p>
Let \(V\) and \(W\) be vector spaces.
Denote by \(\Hom(V, W)\) the set of <a knowl="defs/vec/map">linear maps</a> from \(V\) to \(W\).
<ul>
<li>
<a knowl="facts/vec/hom">This forms a vector space.</a>
</li>
<li>
If \(V = W\), we denote \(\Hom(V, W)\) by \(\End(V)\).
</li>
<li>
We have \(V\simeq\Hom(\mathbf F, V)\).
<details>
<summary>
[explanation]
</summary>
Let \(\Phi:V\to\Hom(\mathbf F, V)\) be given by
\(v\mapsto(\lambda\mapsto\lambda v)\). This map is linear:
[iou]
</details>
</li>
<li>
The set of automorphisms of \(V\) (bijective linear maps
from \(V\) to \(V\)) is denoted \(\Aut(V)\).
</li>
<li>
If \(W = \mathbf F\), we denote \(\Hom(V, W)\) by \(V^*\)
and call this space the <a knowl="defs/vec/dual">dual space</a> of \(V\).
</li>
</ul>
</p>
</body>
</html>
